You are building the backend for a banking application.

Users can request an OTP to reset their password.

Problem:
Some users — or attackers — may spam the “Send OTP” button thousands of times:

* overloading the OTP service
* increasing SMS/email costs
* annoying users
* enabling abuse attacks

To protect the system, the bank decides:

```text id="jup2kt"
A user can request at most 3 OTPs within 5 minutes.
```

If the user exceeds the limit:

* the backend should reject the request
* and ask the user to try again later

Implement:

```java id="6b0s4j"
class RateLimiter {
    boolean allowRequest(String userId)
}
```

Behavior:

* Return `true` if OTP request is allowed
* Return `false` if request should be blocked

Example:

```text id="lmhoq0"
allowRequest("akhil") -> true
allowRequest("akhil") -> true
allowRequest("akhil") -> true
allowRequest("akhil") -> false
```

After 5 minutes, the user should again be able to request OTPs.


Version 2

The banking application becomes very successful.

Initially, the OTP service handled only a few hundred users, so the existing rate limiter worked fine.

But after launch, traffic increased massively:

```text id="m8i76q"
~1 million OTP requests per hour
```

Engineers observed that the current implementation became slow under load.

Problem in current design:
For every incoming OTP request, the system scans a large queue containing requests from all users.

Example:

```text id="jodw5t"
Queue size = 500,000 requests
```

Even if:

```text id="m7n6v3"
User "akhil" has only 2 requests
```

the backend still scans the entire queue.

This increased:

* request latency
* CPU usage
* memory pressure

The bank wants a more scalable design where checking one user's requests does not depend on requests from other users.

Your task:
Redesign the rate limiter to efficiently support millions of users.

The API remains the same:

```java id="ns4m5m"
class RateLimiter {
    boolean allowRequest(String userId)
}
```
